<subSubSection id="C34F6548FFB9FFF2FF1DD9EDFBD6F357" pageId="13" pageNumber="214" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BEA36C3FFB9FFF2FF1DD9EDFBD6F357" blockId="13.[151,1437,927,1097]" pageId="13" pageNumber="214">
This genus currently includes 29 species (ThripsWiki 2020), and these are found widespread in the Old World Tropics. Only two species are recorded in the Neotropics: 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D40FFB9FFF2FD67D9B1FD2BF4C3" baseAuthorityName="Hood" baseAuthorityYear="1928" box="[749,875,963,989]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Helionothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="214" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="funebris">
<emphasis id="B921EAD1FFB9FFF2FD67D9B1FD2BF4C3" box="[749,875,963,989]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="214">H. funebris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="F3427653FFB9FFF2FC3AD9B1FA4DF4C3" box="[944,1037,963,989]" name="Ecuador" pageId="13" pageNumber="214">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="F3427653FFB9FFF2FBC9D9B1FAFDF4C3" box="[1091,1213,963,989]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="13" pageNumber="214">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B32FFB9FFF2FB46D9B1FE93F31C" author="Mound, L. A. &amp; Marullo, R." pageId="13" pageNumber="214" pagination="1 - 488" refId="ref18002" refString="Mound, L. A. &amp; Marullo, R. (1996) The thrips of Central and South America: an introduction (Insecta, Thysanoptera). Memoirs on Entomology, International, 6, 1 - 488." type="journal article" year="1996">Mound &amp; Marullo 1996</bibRefCitation>
), and the widespread pest species 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D40FFB9FFF2FDDED995FC80F31E" baseAuthorityName="Williams" baseAuthorityYear="1916" box="[596,704,999,1024]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Helionothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="214" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="errans">
<emphasis id="B921EAD1FFB9FFF2FDDED995FC80F31E" box="[596,704,999,1024]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="214">H. errans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. According to 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B32FFB9FFF2FCE2D995FACCF31C" author="Mound, L. A. &amp; Marullo, R." box="[872,1164,999,1026]" pageId="13" pageNumber="214" pagination="1 - 488" refId="ref18002" refString="Mound, L. A. &amp; Marullo, R. (1996) The thrips of Central and South America: an introduction (Insecta, Thysanoptera). Memoirs on Entomology, International, 6, 1 - 488." type="journal article" year="1996">Mound &amp; Marullo (1996)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D40FFB9FFF2FB13D995FB57F31F" baseAuthorityName="Hood" baseAuthorityYear="1928" box="[1177,1303,999,1025]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Helionothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="214" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="funebris">
<emphasis id="B921EAD1FFB9FFF2FB13D995FB57F31F" box="[1177,1303,999,1025]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="214">H. funebris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is probably not congeneric with 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D40FFB9FFF2FEF6DE79FC58F33B" authorityName="Bagnall" authorityYear="1932" box="[380,536,1035,1061]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Helionothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="214" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B921EAD1FFB9FFF2FEF6DE79FC58F33B" box="[380,536,1035,1061]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="214">Helionothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the members of which have a prominent transverse ridge on the head, the metanotum with a strongly developed triangular area, and the tergal antecostal ridge usually forming a series of arches.
</paragraph>
